IS  - 5
KW  - State dependence
KW  - unemployment
KW  - nonparametric
KW  - partial identification
KW  - linear programming
KW  - dynamic discrete choice
KW  - moment inequalities
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA14138
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper is about measuring state dependence in dynamic discrete outcomes. I develop a nonparametric dynamic potential outcomes (DPO) model and propose an array of parameters and identifying assumptions that can be considered in this model. I show how to construct sharp identified sets under combinations of identifying assumptions by using a flexible linear programming procedure. I apply the analysis to study state dependence in unemployment for working age high school educated men using an extract from the 2008 Survey of Income and Program Participation (SIPP). Using only nonparametric assumptions, I estimate that state dependence accounts for at least 30?40% of the four-month persistence in unemployment among high school educated men.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - How Destructive Is Innovation?
AU  - Garcia-Macia, Daniel
AU  - Hsieh, Chang-Tai
AU  - Klenow, Peter J.
Y1  - 2019/09/01
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2019/09/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA14930
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
JA  - Econometrica
SP  - 1507
EP  - 1541
VL  - 87
IS  - 5
KW  - Economic growth
KW  - innovation
KW  - creative destruction
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA14930
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Entrants and incumbents can create new products and displace the products of competitors. Incumbents can also improve their existing products. How much of aggregate productivity growth occurs through each of these channels? Using data from the U.S. Longitudinal Business Database on all nonfarm private businesses from 1983 to 2013, we arrive at three main conclusions: First, most growth appears to come from incumbents. We infer this from the modest employment share of entering firms (defined as those less than 5 years old). Second, most growth seems to occur through improvements of existing varieties rather than creation of brand new varieties. Third, own-product improvements by incumbents appear to be more important than creative destruction. We infer this because the distribution of job creation and destruction has thinner tails than implied by a model with a dominant role for creative destruction.
ER  - 

